<p>

<b>GCstar</b> is an application for managing personal collections. Detailed information on each item can be automatically retrieved from the Internet and the user can store additional data, such as the location or whom he/she has lent them to. The user may also search and filter the collection by criteria.</p>
<p>

Current version manages these kind of collections:</p>
<p>

<list>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 Movies</entry>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 Video games</entry>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 Books</entry>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 Music</entry>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 Numismatic</entry>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 Wines</entry>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 Board games</entry>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 Comic books</entry>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 TV shows episodes</entry>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 User defined collections</entry>
</list>
</p>
<p>

GCstar is the successor of <software wordnetid="106566077" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../410/2897410.xml">
GCfilms</link></software>
 that only managed collections of movies.</p>
<p>

__TOC__</p>


<sec>
<st>
 Features </st>

<ss1>
<st>
 Automatic retrieval </st>
<p>

Information concerning an item (from one of the default collection types) can be automatically retrieved from various Internet websites. Only a few information such as a movie title or an <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../919/14919.xml">
ISBN</link> is required to perform the search.</p>

</ss1>
<ss1>
<st>
 Import and export </st>
<p>

GCstar supports importing collections created by other programs such as <weblink xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://periapsis.org/tellico/">
Tellico</weblink>, <system wordnetid="104377057" confidence="0.8">
<artifact wordnetid="100021939" confidence="0.8">
<instrumentality wordnetid="103575240" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../943/1846943.xml">
Alexandria</link></instrumentality>
</artifact>
</system>
 or Ant Movie Catalog.  It could also import some list made in more standard formats such as <format wordnetid="106636806" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../906/501906.xml">
CSV</link></format>
 or a simple list of items names.</p>
<p>

The collections may aso be exported to various formats including <format wordnetid="106636806" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../191/13191.xml">
HTML</link></format>
, <format wordnetid="106636806" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../138/34138.xml">
XML</link></format>
 or <programming_language wordnetid="106898352" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../004/29004.xml">
SQL</link></programming_language>
.</p>

</ss1>
<ss1>
<st>
 Lending managements </st>
<p>

For each item in a collection, it is possible to set it as lended to someone. GCstar manages an history of all the borrowers. It could also send an email to the person that get the item.</p>

</ss1>
</sec>
<sec>
<st>
 The mascot </st>
<p>

The GCstar mascot is the same as the one that GCfilms used. It is a blue periscope named <b>Péri</b>. He was created by <weblink xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://le-spektre.org/">
LE SPEKTRE</weblink>.</p>


</sec>
